
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `brltty-atb` baraye tabdil matn-ha be khatte braille baraye dastgah-haye braille estefade mishavad. In dastoor be BRLTTY komak mikonad ta matn-ha ra be shekl-e dorost baraye nahobinayan namayesh dahad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `--help`  --> ❓ Namayesh rahnamaye dastoor va gozine-ha
    🔹 `--version`  --> ℹ️ Namayesh version-e `brltty-atb`
    🔹 `-l <zaban>` --> 🌐 Entkhab zabane braille (masalan, `en` baraye English)
    🔹 `-t <type>` --> ⌨️ Type terminal ra moshakhas mikonad (masalan, `dumb`)

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ echo "Hello World" | brltty-atb

    🔹 Tabdil matn "Hello World" be khatte braille va namayesh an dar terminal

    $ brltty-atb -l fr < file.txt

    🔹 Tabdil contents file.txt be khatte braille ba zabane faransevi.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ echo "Salam Donya" | brltty-atb -l fa

    🔹 Matn "Salam Donya" be braille farsi tabdil shode va dar terminal namayesh dade mishavad. Agar `-l fa` ezafe nashavad, braille default (engilisi) estefade mishavad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `brltty-atb` command converts text to braille for braille displays. It assists BRLTTY in properly displaying text for visually impaired users.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `--help`  --> ❓ Display command help and options.
    🔹 `--version`  --> ℹ️ Display the version of `brltty-atb`.
    🔹 `-l <language>` --> 🌐 Specify the braille language (e.g., `en` for English).
    🔹 `-t <type>` --> ⌨️  Specify the terminal type (e.g., `dumb`).

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ echo "Hello World" | brltty-atb

    🔹 Converts the text "Hello World" to braille and displays it in the terminal.

    $ brltty-atb -l fr < file.txt

    🔹 Converts the contents of file.txt to braille using the French language.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ echo "Hello World" | brltty-atb -l en

    🔹 The text "Hello World" is converted to English braille and displayed in the terminal. Omitting `-l en` will result in the default braille (often English) being used.
